  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Money laundering is a serious federal crime in the United States, and the penalties can be severe. Under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **USA PATRIOT Act**, the primary statutes governing money laundering are **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956** and **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957**. Here are the key penalties:\n\n### 1. **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956 (Money Laundering)**\n   - **Maximum Penalty**: Up to **20 years in federal prison**.\n   - **Fines**: The greater of **$500,000** or **twice the value of the laundered funds**.\n   - This statute applies to individuals who knowingly engage in financial transactions involving proceeds from unlawful activities with the intent to promote criminal activity, conceal the source of funds, or evade taxes.\n\n### 2. **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957 (Engaging in Monetary Transactions with Criminally Derived Property)**\n   - **Maximum Penalty**: Up to **10 years in federal prison**.\n   - **Fines**: The greater of **$250,000** or **twice the value of the property involved**.\n   - This statute applies to individuals who knowingly engage in transactions involving criminally derived property valued over **$10,000**.\n\n### 3. **Civil Penalties**\n   - Civil penalties can also be imposed, including **fines** and **forfeiture of assets** connected to the money laundering activity.\n   - For example, under **31 U.S.C. \u00a7 5321**, civil penalties for violations of the Bank Secrecy Act can range from **$10,000 per violation** to **$100,000 or more**, depending on the severity and frequency of the violation.\n\n### 4. **Enhanced Penalties for Certain Cases**\n   - If the money laundering involves proceeds from **drug trafficking** or other serious crimes, the penalties can be more severe.\n   - If the offense involves **terrorist financing**, the penalties can include **up to life imprisonment** and **higher fines**.\n\n### 5. **Forfeiture**\n   - The government may **seize and forfeit** any property or funds involved in or derived from money laundering activities.\n\n### 6. **Conspiracy Charges**\n   - Individuals involved in a conspiracy to commit money laundering can face the same penalties as those who directly commit the offense.\n\n### 7. **Corporate Liability**\n   - Businesses and financial institutions can also be held liable for money laundering violations, potentially resulting in **significant fines**, **loss of licenses**, and **reputational damage**.\n\nThese penalties underscore the seriousness of money laundering offenses and the federal government's commitment to combating financial crimes. If you are facing charges related to money laundering, it is essential to consult a qualified attorney experienced in federal criminal law.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
